For the past fifteen years I’ve been making short films and documentaries under various guises. I don’t tend to promote that work on Instagram as I enjoy the separation between stills and motion, but for 2023 I wanted to find a new way to share that side of my professional life. @kindredprojects is that place. I’d be grateful if you check out the page and give it a follow. I’ll be posting a lot of new work there over the coming weeks and would love to find an audience for it. My personal page will remain as it’s always been - a place for photos - until Instagram tells me the human eye no longer registers a still image.
Thanks to everyone who gave my new film profile a follow! Here’s a trailer for a film we made in Oaxaca last year about the ancient craft of Mezcal making. Check it out @kindredprojects

If you watched the short film Palenque I posted on @kindredprojects recently you’ll recognize @casasilencio, the stunning boutique hotel component of a working mezcal distillery in Oaxaca. Designed by architect @alejandrodacostalopez and sitting at the foot of a long and historic valley, Casa Silencio is both mysterious and enticing. Not only is my friend @dwhartman extremely photogenic and a wonderful fellow, he also happens to be a fantastic writer whose first book is coming out next week:
“Battle of Ink and Ice deftly connects Arctic exploration and the emergence of modern media in the late 19th and early 20th centuries”

In late 2021 I found myself at 8000ft, high in the Sierra Madre del Sur mountains. There, perched at the edge of the world was this little sauna, smoky and cracked and perfect. 

It’s one of many incredible spots highlighted in the new(ish) book by @lady_bro of @cabinlove called THERMAL, out now on @chroniclebooks
.

From a recent morning spent in the enlightening company of @woodlandpantry. We met up at first light and hiked up the valley toward the meadow, all the while talking about the history of the land and the incredible gifts it provides when left in its wild form, and in spite of human impact the speed and creativity in which it can bounce back is electrifying.

Tanya is a forest farmer, plant steward, herbalist and kitchen witch, using foraged and intentionally grown plants and flowers to bring out their inherent healing powers. Follow @woodlandpantry for more on her work!
.

Hi folks - I’m doing another print sale for the pre-Christmas period. This year I am altering it slightly. I am ordering special, limited edition prints from a trusted printer and taking orders by email or DM only. Furthermore 20% of all profits will go to the @internationalmedicalcorps, to help bring medical supplies to civilians trapped by wars in Ukraine, Israel, Gaza and beyond. 

I will be doing non-framed 16x20 prints, and while I have some suggested prints, most of my non-client work is available on request - check out my site or my Instagram and DM me or email pbcrosby@gmail.com with any requests.

*I would also point out I have some beautifully framed prints in stores upstate to which I’d be happy to point you towards

I alluded to the rumored history of Castle Rock in a previous post. First completed in 1881, it sits austerely on a prominent hill above the town of Peekskill, and may have acted as inspiration for author L Frank Baum for the Emerald Castle who lived in the town for a period (at that time there was also a road in Peekskill with bricks painted yellow). In recent years the castle has been undergoing significant renovations headed by @hudsondesignarchitecture

For the past couple of months I’ve been working on a project with some of the best people I know in the Catskills - a story about how we interact with our environment and the wildlife within that will become a feature documentary. Centered around the discoveries of my friends @cabin_trail_cam and featuring the likes of @theoutsideinstitute, @catskilltracks, @woodlandpantry and many more, I can’t wait to share where this little project goes.
